# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2017-giro-d-italia
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] The **1909 Giro d'Italia** was the 1st edition of the Giro d'Italia, organized and sponsored by the Italian major sport newspaper *La Gazzetta dello Sport*.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] The event began in Milan on 13 May with a 397 km (247 mi) first stage to Bologna, finishing back in Milan on 30 May after a final stage of 206 km (128 mi) and a total distance covered of 2,447.9 km (1,521 mi).
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] The race was won by the Italian rider Luigi Ganna of the Atala team, with fellow Italians Carlo Galetti and Giovanni Rossignoli coming in second and third respectively.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] Conceived by *La Gazzetta* to boost its circulation at the expense of its rival *Corriere della Sera*, the 1909 Giro was the first stage road race.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] Its eight stages, although relatively few compared to modern Grand Tours, were each much longer than those raced today.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] The event began with a long primarily flat stage that was won by Dario Beni.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] He lost the lead after the next stage to the eventual winner Luigi Ganna, who in turn lost it to Carlo Galetti after the mountainous third stage.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] Ganna regained the lead after the fourth stage and successfully defended it all the way to the finish in Milan, winning three stages en route.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] The idea of holding a bicycle race around Italy was first suggested in a telegram sent by Tullo Margagni, editor of *La Gazzetta dello Sport*, to the paper's owner Emilio Costamagna and cycling editor Armando Cougnet.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] *La Gazzetta'*s rival, *Corriere della Sera* was planning to hold a bicycle race of its own, flushed with the success of its automobile race.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] Morgagni decided to try and hold the race before *Corriere della Sera* could hold theirs, and following *La Gazzetta*'s success in creating the Giro di Lombardia and Milan–San Remo, Costamagna decided to back the idea.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] The inaugural Giro d'Italia bicycle race was announced on 7 August 1908 in the first page of that day's edition of *La Gazzetta*, to be held in May 1909.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] The idea of the race was influenced by the success of the French magazine *L'Auto*'s organization of the Tour de France.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] Since the newspaper lacked the necessary 25,000 lire to sponsor the race, the organizers consulted Primo Bongrani, a sympathetic accountant at the bank Cassa di Risparmio.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] He proceeded to solicit donations from all over Italy, and succeeded in raising sufficient money to cover the operating costs.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] The prize money came from a casino in San Remo after Francesco Sghirla, a former *Gazzetta* employee, encouraged them to contribute to the race.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] Even *Corriere*, *La Gazzetta'*s rival, donated 3,000 lire.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] Both teams and individual riders were allowed to enter the race, which was run in eight stages with two to three rest days between each stage.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] Compared to modern races the stages were extraordinarily long, with an average distance of more than 300 km (190 mi), compared to the 165 km (103 mi) average stage length in the 2012 Giro d'Italia.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] The route was primarily flat, although it did contain a few major ascents.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] The third stage contained ascents to Macerone, Rionero Sannitico, and Roccaraso.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] The Giro's sixth stage contained only one pass, the Passo Bracco.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] The seventh stage was the last to contain any major ascents: the climbs of the Colle di Nava and the ascent to San Bartolomeo.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] Riders were required to sign in at checkpoints during each stage to minimize the opportunities for cheating; they were also photographed at the beginning and end of each stage, and the images compared by the judges.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] Riders could receive assistance when repairing their bicycles, but were not allowed to replace their machines if they became damaged during the course of the stage.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] The inaugural Giro used a points system to determine the race winner.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] The organizers chose to have a points system over a system based around elapsed time after the scandal that engulfed the 1904 Tour de France.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] Another factor in the organizer's decision was that it would be cheaper to count the placings of the riders rather than clocking their times during each stage.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] The race leader was determined by adding up each rider's placing in each stage.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] Thus if a rider placed second in the first stage and third in the second stage he would have a total of five points, and whoever had the lowest points total was the leader.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] Under this system Luigi Ganna was declared the winner, but had the Giro been a time-based event he would have lost to the third-place finisher Giovanni Rossignoli by 37 minutes.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] The winner of the general classification received a grand prize of 5,325 lire.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] Every rider who finished the race with more than 100 points without winning any prizes in any of the stages was given 100 lire.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] A total of 166 riders signed up to participate in the event.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] Twenty of the riders who entered were non-Italians: fifteen were French, two were German, one was Argentinian, one was Belgian, and one was from Trieste, which at the time was not a part of Italy.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] Only 127 riders started the first stage of the race, all but five of Italian descent, of whom only 49 reached the finish in Milan on 30 May.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] Riders were allowed to enter the race as independents or as a member of a team.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] The two best-known Italians taking part in the race were Luigi Ganna and Giovanni Gerbi.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] Gerbi was the more successful of the two, having won the Giro di Lombardia, the Milano–Torino, and several other one-day races.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] Ganna had won Milan–San Remo earlier the same year – notably the first Italian winner of the race.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] The peloton also featured two Tour de France winners, Louis Trousselier and Lucien Petit-Breton, as well as two future Giro d'Italia winners: Carlo Galetti and Carlo Oriani.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] The inaugural Giro d'Italia's first stage, 397 km (247 mi) from Milan to Bologna, began on 13 May 1909 at 2:53 am in front of a large crowd.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] 127 riders set off from the starting line outside *La Gazzetta*'s headquarters in the Piazzale Loreto.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] The stage was marred by mechanical issues and crashes owing to bad weather, the first mass crash occurring before dawn less than 2 km (1 mi) from the start.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] Luigi Ganna, leading after the first real climb near Lake Garda, was delayed by a puncture with about 70 km (43 mi) to go and the other racers attacked, but he caught them again after they were stopped by a train crossing.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] The leading riders then made their way into Bologna, where Dario Beni won the stage.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] The second stage, 378.5 km (235 mi) long, saw the first uphill finish, into Chieti, where Giovanni Cuniolo edged out Ganna for the stage win.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] Ganna's second place was nevertheless high enough to make him the new race leader.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] The third stage, to Naples, was 242.8 km (151 mi).
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] Before the start, three riders were disqualified and subsequently removed from the race for taking a train during the second stage.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] They were caught after failing to pass through an unexpected checkpoint set up by the organizers.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] The start of the third stage was moved downhill after the opening descent was found to be too dangerous for the participants' brakes.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] After the mountains Giovanni Rossignoli pursued the leader, Carlo Galetti, eventually catching him and going on to win the stage, while Galetti took the race lead away from Ganna.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] On the fourth stage, 228.1 km (142 mi) from Naples to the Italian capital Rome, French rider Louis Trousselier was doing well until he ran over tacks strewn on the road by spectators, and the other riders left him behind.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] Galetti and Ganna formed a group at the front and Ganna went on to win the stage in front of thousands of spectators, retaking the race lead by a single point.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] The fifth stage was 346.5 km (215 mi) to Florence.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] Like the fourth, it was plagued by punctures.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] Luigi Ganna led until he had a flat tyre with about 10 km (6 mi) to go.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] A few riders passed him as he repaired it but he chased them down and won the stage.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] On the sixth stage, 294.4 km (183 mi) from Florence to Genoa, Carlo Galetti and Giovanni Rossignoli broke away from the leading group of seven as they neared the downhill finish, with Rossignoli winning the stage in front of a large crowd.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] Race leader Ganna had suffered more punctures but managed to fight his way back to finish third.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] The seventh stage, 357 km (222 mi), was scheduled to run from Genoa to Turin.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] Massive crowds at the start led Armando Cougnet to introduce a rule forbidding riders to attack over the first few kilometers until the peloton was outside the city and the race proper could begin.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] There was also rumored to be close to 50,000 spectators and a bakers' strike in Turin, so Cougnet switched the finish to the city of Beinasco, about 6 km (4 mi) short of Turin.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] Ganna and Rossignoli led for most of the stage until about 6 km (4 mi) before the finish, when Ganna attacked and Rossignoli could not counter.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] Ganna's win extended his race lead over Carlo Galetti.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] The eighth and final stage started in Turin, covered 206 km (128 mi), and finished in Milan in front of a crowd of more than 30,000.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] Ganna was amongst the leading group until he suffered a flat tyre.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] He managed to fight his way back until, with the leaders in sight, he had another puncture.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] The leading group pulled away until the race directors stopped them to let Ganna catch up.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] Escorted by mounted police, the riders then made their way into Milan's Arena Civica stadium for the finish.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] As the racers geared up for the sprint finish a police horse fell, causing a few riders to crash.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] Dario Beni avoided the incident and edged out Galetti for the stage win, with Ganna coming in third.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] Thus Ganna became the first winner of the Giro d'Italia.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] He and his team, Atala, also won the team classification.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] Forty-nine cyclists completed all eight stages.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] The points each received from their stage placings were added up for the general classification, and the winner was the rider with the fewest accumulated points.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] Ernesto Azzini won the prize for best ranked isolati rider in the general classification.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] The first Giro d'Italia was a great success, prompting organizers to arrange a second one for 1910.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] The race substantially increased *La Gazzetta'*s circulation, and the starts and finishes were attended by large audiences.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] Ganna's prize money helped him start his own bike factory in 1912.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1909-giro-d-italia] The newspaper ran the event through 1988, when the RCS Organizzazzioni Sportivi company was created to run it.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1910-giro-d-italia] The **1910 Giro d'Italia** was the second edition of the Giro d'Italia, a Grand Tour organized and sponsored by the newspaper *La Gazzetta dello Sport*.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1910-giro-d-italia] The race began on 18 May in Milan with a stage that stretched 388 km (241 mi) to Udine, finishing back in Milan on 5 June after a 277.5 km (172 mi) stage and a total distance covered of 2,987.4 km (1,856 mi).
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1910-giro-d-italia] The race was won by the Italian rider Carlo Galetti of the Atala-Continental team, with fellow Italians Eberardo Pavesi and Luigi Ganna coming in second and third respectively.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1910-giro-d-italia] Eberardo Pavesi was the first rider to lead the race after winning the first stage into Udine.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1910-giro-d-italia] After the second stage, Carlo Galetti took the lead of the race.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1910-giro-d-italia] Galetti then successfully defended the lead all the way to the race's finish in Milan.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1910-giro-d-italia] En route to his overall victory, Galetti won two stages.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1910-giro-d-italia] The Atala-Continental team finished as winners of the team classification.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1910-giro-d-italia] One major change was made to the calculation for the general classification before the start of the second Giro d'Italia.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1910-giro-d-italia] Originally a point was given to each rider for his placing on each stage, but the organizers chose to give the riders who placed 51st or higher in a stage 51 points and keep the point distribution system the same for the riders who placed 1st through 50th in a stage.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1910-giro-d-italia] The organizers chose to increase the length of their race after the success from the first edition.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1910-giro-d-italia] The original race was eight stages long and the 1910 edition was increased by two stages, to ten.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1910-giro-d-italia] The overall length of the race was increased to close to 3,000 kilometers, which made the race close to 500 kilometers longer than the inaugural edition of the race.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1910-giro-d-italia] A total of 101 riders started the second Giro d'Italia out of the 118 that signed up to participate.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1910-giro-d-italia] Of the 101 riders that began the Giro d'Italia on 18 May, twenty of them made it to the finish in Milan on 5 June.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1910-giro-d-italia] Riders were allowed to ride on their own or as a member of a team.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1910-giro-d-italia] There were six teams that competed in the race: Atala-Continental, Atena-Dunlop, Bianchi-Dunlop, Legnano-Dunlop, Otav-Pirelli, and Stucchi-Pirelli.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1910-giro-d-italia] The notable participants included the reigning champion of the Giro d'Italia, Luigi Ganna.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1910-giro-d-italia] The peloton also contained some of the most famous Italian cyclists at the time in Carlo Galetti, Ezio Corlaita, Giovanni Rossignoli, and Eberardo Pavesi.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1910-giro-d-italia] Two-time Tour de France champion Lucien Petit-Breton rode the Giro for the second straight year, along with his fellow countryman Jean-Baptiste Dortignacq who had been successful in the Tour.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1910-giro-d-italia] The Giro also saw its first German participants, neither of whom completed the race.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1910-giro-d-italia] The first stage of the second Giro d'Italia began with a large send off in the start city of Milan.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1910-giro-d-italia] The finish in Udine was hotly contested as five riders came to the finish line in a pack.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1910-giro-d-italia] Ernesto Azzini managed to out-sprint the other four riders in the leading group to win the stage.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1910-giro-d-italia] The next stage saw the first non-Italian stage winner in the history of the Giro d'Italia, the Frenchman Jean-Baptiste Dortignacq.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1910-giro-d-italia] Dortignacq managed to breakaway from his fellow group member Carlo Galetti and then solo to the stage victory while five other riders chased close behind.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1910-giro-d-italia] Galetti's second-place finish on the stage was high enough for him to take the lead of the race.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1910-giro-d-italia] The French success enraged the Italian fans and led the competing riders to ban unite against the foreign riders.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1910-giro-d-italia] The third stage saw three major Italian riders, Luigi Ganna, Carlo Galetti, and Eberardo Pavesi, and attack early on in the stage.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1910-giro-d-italia] The three riders then rode together all the way to the finish in Teramo.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1910-giro-d-italia] Galetti went on to win the stage, with Ganna and Pavesi following in quick succession.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1910-giro-d-italia] The Giro's fourth stage saw a tough stage with poor conditions for the riders, which ultimately led to the withdrawal of many riders including the likes of Lucien Petit-Breton - who was ranked third overall at the time.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1910-giro-d-italia] The peloton's pace was slower due to the w poor conditions, which caused the riders to arrive two hours later than expected in Naples.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1910-giro-d-italia] Pierino Albini beat out the Frenchman Maurice Brocco by 36 seconds for stage victory.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1910-giro-d-italia] Prior to the fifth stage's start, Frenchman Jean-Baptiste Dortignacq withdrew from the race after citing an illness.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1910-giro-d-italia] The police suspected foul play and looked into the situation, but their results are disputed through contradicting stories.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1910-giro-d-italia] Due to impassable roads, the start of the fifth stage was moved from Naples to Capua and decreased the distance of the stage from 224.1 km (139 mi) to 192.3 km (119 mi).
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1910-giro-d-italia] Eberardo Pavesi won the fifth stage after leading for most of the race.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1910-giro-d-italia] The peloton remained intact for roughly the first half of the sixth stage.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1910-giro-d-italia] Luigi Ganna and Carlo Galetti broke away from the pack and made it to the finish in Rome where Ganna then edged out Galetti for the stage victory.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1910-giro-d-italia] During the next stage, a group of six riders lead for the most part before Galetti and Ganna broke away again.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1910-giro-d-italia] The two riders made their way to the finish in Genoa, where a large crowd of spectators came to see the finish.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1910-giro-d-italia] Ganna went on to win his second consecutive stage, while Galetti extended his lead over the rest of the field.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1910-giro-d-italia] The race's eighth stage contained some harsh climbs, most notably the Giovi.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1910-giro-d-italia] The finish of the stage was hotly contested as Galetti, Ganna, and Eberardo Pavesi finished at the same time, with Galetti winning the stage in the end.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1910-giro-d-italia] Eberardo Pavesi dominated the difficult ninth stage that contained the major climbs of the Nava, Tenda, and San Bartolomeo.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1910-giro-d-italia] Pavesi went on to win the stage by close to six minutes over the second-place finisher Luigi Ganna.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1910-giro-d-italia] The race's tenth and final stage was marred by rain.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1910-giro-d-italia] Race leader Carlo Galetti crashed into a hay wagon early on in the stage and sustained some heavy wounds, he would get back on his bike and finish the stage in fifth place.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1910-giro-d-italia] Despite the rain in Milan, many spectators still came to watch the riders arrive.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1910-giro-d-italia] Luigi Ganna was the first rider to cross the finish line in Milan and in doing so, he won his third stage of the 1910 Giro d'Italia.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1910-giro-d-italia] Carlo Galetti won the Giro d'Italia by a margin of eighteen points over Pavesi.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1910-giro-d-italia] Galetti and his team, Atala-Continental, won the team classification.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1910-giro-d-italia] There were 20 cyclists who had completed all ten stages.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1910-giro-d-italia] For these cyclists, the points they received from each of their stage placing's were added up for the general classification.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1910-giro-d-italia] The cyclist with the least accumulated points was the winner.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1910-giro-d-italia] Ezio Corlaita won the prize for best ranked isolati rider in the general classification.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1911-giro-d-italia] The **1911 Giro d'Italia** was the third edition of the Giro d'Italia, a Grand Tour set up and sponsored by the newspaper *La Gazzetta dello Sport*.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1911-giro-d-italia] The race began on 18 May in Rome with a stage that stretched 394.1 km (245 mi) to Florence.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1911-giro-d-italia] It was composed of twelve stages that covered a total distance of 3,530.3 km (2,194 mi).
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1911-giro-d-italia] The race came to a close back in Rome on 6 June after a 266.9 km (166 mi) stage.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1911-giro-d-italia] The race was won by the Italian rider Carlo Galetti of the Bianchi team.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1911-giro-d-italia] Second and third respectively were the Italian riders Giovanni Rossignoli and Giovanni Gerbi.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1911-giro-d-italia] Returning champion Carlo Galetti won the race's opening stage into Florence and was the first to lead the race.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1911-giro-d-italia] He lost the lead to Giovanni Rossignoli after Galetti finished poorly on the race's second stage.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1911-giro-d-italia] Rossignoli held the lead for four days after Galetti took back the lead after the sixth stage.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1911-giro-d-italia] Frenchman Lucien Petit-Breton became the first non-Italian to lead the Giro d'Italia after the race's ninth stage.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1911-giro-d-italia] Petit-Breton lost the lead the next day to Galetti, who then held it all the way to the race's conclusion in Rome.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1911-giro-d-italia] In both 1909 and 1910 Milan had served as both the start and finish of the Giro d'Italia.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1911-giro-d-italia] The organizers chose to honor the 50th anniversary of the unification of Italy by holding the start and finish of the Giro in the Italian capital of Rome.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1911-giro-d-italia] The organizers chose to expand the Giro d'Italia from ten to twelve stages after its great success.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1911-giro-d-italia] The race also saw an increase of close to 500 kilometers in length.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1911-giro-d-italia] The organizers also included the first climb above 2000 meters in the race, the Sestriere.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1911-giro-d-italia] This was also the first edition of the Giro to go deep down into the southern part of Italy, specifically the Bari.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1911-giro-d-italia] Of the 86 riders that began the Giro d'Italia on 15 May, 24 of them made it to the finish in Rome on 6 June.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1911-giro-d-italia] There were five teams that competed in the race: Atala-Dunlop, Bianchi-Pirelli, Fiat-Pirelli, Legnano-Dunlop, and Senior-Polack.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1911-giro-d-italia] The peloton was composed of primarily Italians.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1911-giro-d-italia] The field featured two former Giro d'Italia champions in the 1909 winner Luigi Ganna and returning champion Carlo Galetti.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1911-giro-d-italia] Other notable Italian riders included Giovanni Rossignoli, Eberardo Pavesi, and Giovanni Gerbi.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1911-giro-d-italia] Two-time Tour de France winner Lucien Petit-Breton also competed in the race.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1911-giro-d-italia] The first stage began on 15 May and stretched from Rome to Florence.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1911-giro-d-italia] The racing that day was marred by heavy rain, which led to ten withdrawals.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1911-giro-d-italia] Carlo Galetti won the stage ahead of Giovanni Rossignoli and Dario Beni.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1911-giro-d-italia] The next leg was also dogged by rain and very poor conditions on the road and saw the climbing of the Colle de Bacco.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1911-giro-d-italia] Giovanni Gerbi was the first rider to summit the Colle de Bacco.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1911-giro-d-italia] The climb wore Gerbi out and he was caught and passed by three riders and ultimately finished fourth on the stage.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1911-giro-d-italia] Vincenzo Borgarello was the first rider to cross the finish line in Genoa and won the stage, where a large crowd waited for the riders to finish.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1911-giro-d-italia] Rossignoli took the race lead after finishing two positions in front of Galetti.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1911-giro-d-italia] The race's third day of racing was the first to have clear weather.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1911-giro-d-italia] Race leader Rossignoli bested the likes of Giovanni Gerbi and Carlo Durando to win the stage and consolidate his lead in the general classification.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1911-giro-d-italia] The next stage was hotly contested, with the peloton staying together for the whole stage as Carlo Galetti took the stage win.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1911-giro-d-italia] The race's fifth stage is considered to be the first real mountain stage in Giro d'Italia history.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1911-giro-d-italia] The stage contained the climb of the Sestriere which rises over 2,000 meters.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1911-giro-d-italia] As the race entered the Val Chisone leading up the Sestriere, the peloton ran into muddy roads, which forced many to walk their bikes.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1911-giro-d-italia] Frenchman Lucien Petit-Breton led the riders up the slopes before cracking near the snowy summit.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1911-giro-d-italia] He was passed first by Ezio Corlaita, who was the first to summit the Sestriere, and then by many other riders.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1911-giro-d-italia] Petit-Breton caught up with the leading riders on the long descent and rode into the finish in Turin with Corlaita, Rossignoli, and Galetti.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1911-giro-d-italia] Petit-Breton edged out Galetti for the stage win as Galetti tied Rossignoli for the overall lead.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1911-giro-d-italia] The riders started the sixth stage in Turin with a large number of people in attendance for the sendoff.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1911-giro-d-italia] Giuseppe Santhià took the stage as the riders rolled over the packed finish line in Milan.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1911-giro-d-italia] Dario Beni soloed to victory in the seventh leg, finishing over a minute ahead of the second-place finisher Santhià.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1911-giro-d-italia] The next stage was won by Lauro Bordin as Galetti extended his overall lead by a single point over Rossignoli.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1911-giro-d-italia] Ezio Corlaita won the Giro's ninth stage, while Lucien Petit-Breton took the race lead and doing so, became the first non-Italian to lead the Giro d'Italia.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1911-giro-d-italia] In the following stage, the leading breakaway contained six riders – race leader Petit-Breton and five Bianchi riders – and rode into the finish in Bari together.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1911-giro-d-italia] Carlo Galetti took the stage win and the race lead, while Petit-Breton finished in sixth place on the day and was pushed down to second overall.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1911-giro-d-italia] The race's penultimate day of racing was scheduled to go from Bari to Naples.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1911-giro-d-italia] During the stage, Lucien Petit-Breton crashed and was forced to abandon the race.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1911-giro-d-italia] The route had the riders go through rough roads that were heavy with dust and occasional passed over streams, thus flooding the roads.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1911-giro-d-italia] The riders were also chase by enraged buffalo.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1911-giro-d-italia] All of those factors caused the riders to end the stage a few kilometers short of Naples, in Pompeii with Alfredo Sivocci winning the day.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1911-giro-d-italia] The last stage ended back in Rome, where the race began.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1911-giro-d-italia] Ezio Corlaita took his second stage win as 24 riders that began the Giro finished the day.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1911-giro-d-italia] Bianchi's Carlo Galetti became the first rider to win two editions of the Giro d'Italia.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1911-giro-d-italia] There were 24 cyclists who had completed all twelve stages.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1911-giro-d-italia] The cyclist with the fewest accumulated points was the winner.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1911-giro-d-italia] Giovanni Gerbi won the prize for best ranked isolati rider in the general classification.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] The **1912 Giro d'Italia** was the fourth edition of the Giro d'Italia, a Grand Tour set up and sponsored by the newspaper *La Gazzetta dello Sport*.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] The race began on 19 May in Milan with a stage that stretched 398.8 km (248 mi) to Padua.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] The race was composed of nine stages that covered a total distance of 2,733.6 km (1,699 mi).
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] The race came to a close in Bergamo on 4 June after a 235 km (146 mi) stage.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] The race was won by the Atala-Dunlop team that finished with Carlo Galetti, Eberardo Pavesi, and Giovanni Micheletto.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] Second and third respectively were Peugeot and Gerbi.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] The calculation of the general classification changed from the previous editions of the race, shifting to a team-based event, with each team only allowed four riders.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] Points were awarded to teams based upon winning the stage, having multiple riders in the top four places in each stage, and finishing the stage with a minimum of three riders.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] A total of fourteen teams participated, with 56 riders registering and 54 officially starting the race.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] Micheletto won the opening stage of the race to give Atala-Dunlop the first lead in the race.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] Despite two consecutive stage wins by Legnano riders, Atala-Dunlop still retained the lead going into the fourth stage.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] The fourth leg was held in rainy conditions that caused some rivers to overflow on the course and riders to take the wrong roads for extensive distances; this led to the cancellation of the stage and addition of a ninth leg that drew some of its route from the Giro di Lombardia.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] An Atala-Dunlop rider won the fifth stage, but the team lost the lead to Peugeot for one stage.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] Following the stage, Atala-Dunlop regained the lead and held that to the race's finish in Bergamo.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] Outside the yearly changes in the route, race length, and number of stages, the biggest change was in how the general classification was to be calculated.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] The organizers chose to make the general classification centered on teams rather than individuals as the race was contested in the first three years of its existence.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] They chose to only allow teams of four riders to compete in the race, making this the first Giro d'Italia to not contain any independent riders.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] Each team was required to have three riders finish each stage in order to remain in the race.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] The general classification was still determined by a point system: four points went to the team that the stage winner came from, if a team got two riders in the top four placings on a stage they got two points, and if a team completed the stage with the minimum three riders, they earned one point.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] The new point system for the general classification was met with some resistance as many people were very confused by how the new system operated or simply preferred the original system the organizers had used in years past.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] In response to the confusion surrounding the general classification format, the race organizers released a supplement to help better explain how the new points system operated.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] A *La Stampa* writer claimed that the supplement provided several lengthy example calculations and stated that they would know after the first stage how successful this new system would be.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] The team that won general classification won a grand prize of 4000 lire.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] The runner-up of the race received 2000 lire, third was rewarded with 1000 lire, fourth got 600 lire, and fifth place received 400 lire.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] Each stage winner received 600 lire and second place on the day got 300 lire.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] Of the 56 riders that signed up to participate in the 1912 Giro d'Italia, 54 of them began the race on 19 May.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] Since the race's general classification was to be based around team points there were no independent riders as in years past.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] The organizers allowed the participating teams to have up to four riders, with each team needing three riders to finish each stage to remain in the race.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] There were a total of fourteen teams that started the 1912 Giro d'Italia.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] A French team was planning on competing in the race, but opted not to and so all the teams that competed were based in Italy.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] This edition of the Giro d'Italia saw the first teams enter the race that were not sponsored by a bicycle related industry.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] Each team was required to wear identical colored jerseys.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] Atala-Dunlop was the favorite going into the race as the team was composed of 1909 winner Luigi Ganna, two-time winner Carlo Galetti, Giovanni Micheletto, and Eberardo Pavesi.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] The team was collectively known as "The Four Musketeers." The Gerbi team contained last year's third-place finisher Giovanni Gerbi, last year's runner-up and stage winner Giovanni Rossignoli, and former stage winner Pierino Albini.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] Legnano, Bianchi and Peugeot were also seen as contenders for the overall victory.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] The race also featured future Giro d'Italia winner Carlo Oriani who competed for the Stucchi team.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] The race was planned to begin at 2:30 AM local time by the organizers, but due to large crowds and some participants arriving late, the race officially started at 2:43.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] The riders formed three groups on the road, of which the first one contained twenty riders when it passed through the checkpoint in Brescia.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] The group further thinned to sixteen by the time it reached Verona, and to eleven when it arrived at the checkpoint in Vicenza.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] From the group, the sprint to the finish line was mainly contested by Giovanni Micheletto and Giuseppe Santhià, of which the former managed to win the leg.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] With Atala-Dunlop's Micheletto winning the stage and his teammate Carlo Galetti finishing third, Atala-Dunlop acquired seven points and the lead in the race.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] The second stage of the race saw a large group of around forty riders enter Mantua after over one hundred kilometers of racing.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] After the group broke into five or six smaller groups due to a large crash and in part due issues brought about by heavy fog.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] A group of seven was first to reach the stage's finish in Bologna, where Bianchi's Vincenzo Borgarello won the sprint to the line.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] Stage 3 began under heavy cloud coverage.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] The leading group on the road was reduced as the stage traversed the hillier portions of the stage.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] Ernesto Azzini of the Legnano team won the stage after edging out Eberardo Pavesi.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] The race's fourth stage saw very rainy conditions throughout, which caused the roads to turn muddy and streams nearby the roads to overflow.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] The thirty riders that began the stage took the wrong turn onto Sabina rode for over 50 km (31 mi), once they had reached Civita Castellana, before realizing their errors.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] This, when combined with the weather and road conditions, caused the riders to protest to the race jury and get the stage cancelled.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] The riders then road a train to Rome for the start of the next stage.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] At the finish in Rome there were over 20,000 paying spectators waiting to see the finish of the stage.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] When news broke of the stage's cancelling, the spectators grew angry and the organizers refunded their tickets they had purchased to view the race.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] The route of the added ninth stage came from the route of the Giro di Lombardia, despite the initial protest of the Italian Velocopie Union.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] The prize money for the stage was split among the fourteen riders that noticed the mistake.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] Atala-Dunlop's Luigi Ganna abandoned the race during the fifth stage due to injuries suffered from a crash during the fourth stage before it was cancelled.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] Galetti won the fifth leg, but with the placings on the stage, Peugeot took the race lead from Atala-Dunlop.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] Rain marred the start of the sixth stage at 6:40 local time, as well as most of the stage itself.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] A group of sixteen riders formed at the front of the race and was later reduced to ten before passing through Lucca.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] Lauro Bordin of the Gerbi team attacked and went on to ride solo, reaching the checkpoint in Spezia fifteen minutes quicker than Azzini, Cocchi, and Agostoni.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] Bordin reached the finish first, eighteen minutes ahead of the second-place finisher.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] Borgarello won his second stage with his victory in the seventh stage, out-sprinting Micheletto and Carlo Durando.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] In the final sprint, Micheletto felt that Durando encroached him and moved ahead; this action caused the Italian fans to rush on to the track in anger.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] The police then moved the two riders to a bar, until the crowd dispersed.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] Micheletto won his second stage of the race two days later.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] Before the start of the final stage, Micheletto became sick and Pavesi convinced him to continue the race and finish the final stage.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] Borgarello won his third stage of the race, while Atala-Dunlop consolidated their lead and the race win by having two riders, Micheletto and Galetti, finish in the top four.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] There were five teams who had completed all nine stages with the required number of riders.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] For these teams, the points they received from each of their stage placing's were added up for the general classification.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] The team with the most accumulated points was the winner.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] The race organizers, *La Gazzetta dello Sport* recognized the team point system was not a success and reverted to the individual point based system for the general classification for the 1913 edition.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] Despite the failure of the team system, the newspaper still achieved success with the race, causing them to shift to a daily newspaper rather than three times a week.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1912-giro-d-italia] If the race had been contested based upon the time it took to complete each stage and their respective sum for each rider, the race would have been won by Carlo Galetti.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1913-giro-d-italia] The **1913 Giro d'Italia** was the fifth edition of the Giro d'Italia, a Grand Tour organized and sponsored by the newspaper *La Gazzetta dello Sport*.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1913-giro-d-italia] The race began on 6 May in Milan with a stage that stretched 341 km (212 mi) to Genoa, finishing back in Milan on 22 May after a 321.1 km (200 mi) stage and a total distance covered of 2,932 km (1,822 mi).
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1913-giro-d-italia] The race was won by the Italian rider Carlo Oriani of the Maino team.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1913-giro-d-italia] Second and third respectively were the Italian riders Eberardo Pavesi and Giuseppe Azzini.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1913-giro-d-italia] It was the last Giro with a final classification in points and the first one in which the final winner of the race did not win a single stage.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1913-giro-d-italia] The Giro saw the debut of the twenty-year-old Costante Girardengo, who won the 6th stage.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1913-giro-d-italia] The 1913 Giro was the last concluded by Luigi Ganna, winner of the first edition.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1913-giro-d-italia] Outside the yearly changes in the route, race length, and number of stages, the biggest change to how the general classification was to be calculated.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1913-giro-d-italia] The race organizers decided to change back to the way the general classification had been calculated in the earlier editions, by the individual and the awarding of points based on how high the rider placed in each stage rather than doing a team points based system like the previous edition.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1913-giro-d-italia] Of the 99 riders that began the Giro d'Italia on 6 May, 35 of them made it to the finish in Milan on 22 May.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1913-giro-d-italia] There were eight teams that competed in the race: Ganna-Dunlop, Gerbi-Dunlop, Globo-Dunlop, Legnano-Dunlop, Maino-Pirelli, Otav-Pirelli, Peugeot Italy-Tedeschi, and Stucchi-Dunlop.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1913-giro-d-italia] The peloton was composed completely of Italians.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1913-giro-d-italia] The field featured three former Giro d'Italia champions in the 1909 winner Luigi Ganna, three-time winner and returning champion Carlo Galetti, and returning champion Eberardo Pavesi.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1913-giro-d-italia] Other notable Italian riders that started the race included Giovanni Rossignoli, Alfredo Sivocci, Carlo Oriani, and Giuseppe Azzini.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1913-giro-d-italia] Among the riders was Edoardo Bardelli, who had recently turned seventeen.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1913-giro-d-italia] Bardelli is the youngest rider to have started the Giro d'Italia.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1913-giro-d-italia] The first stage ended with a sprint between Santhia and Albini; Santhia won and became the first leader.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1913-giro-d-italia] In the second stage, Pavesi suffered from a flat tire, but he was able to get back to the peloton, and then get away from the other riders, finishing alone.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1913-giro-d-italia] In the third stage, a large group stayed together until the last checkpoint in Narni.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1913-giro-d-italia] There, the soigneurs of the Legnano cycling team (with Borgarello, Albini, Pavesi, Albini and Canepari) had not arrived yet, so they could not get their foods and drinks.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1913-giro-d-italia] Santhia and Azzini saw an opportunity and escaped; when Azzini had a flat tire, Santhia continued alone, and won the stage, becoming the leader of the general classification.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1913-giro-d-italia] Stage four was won by Giuseppe Azzini, in his first year as a professional cyclist.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1913-giro-d-italia] Santhia finished in third place, keeping the overall lead.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1913-giro-d-italia] An important event in that stage was a late flat tire for Santhia.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1913-giro-d-italia] Because of his low position in the stage, he lost the overall lead to Pavesi.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1913-giro-d-italia] In the sixth stage, Santhia abandoned because he was ill.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1913-giro-d-italia] A young Costante Girardengo won this stage, the first of 30 stage victories in the Giro.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1913-giro-d-italia] The seventh stage was won by Canepari, in a long solo escape.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1913-giro-d-italia] Pavesi finished the stage in twelfth place, and lost the lead to Azzini, who was only one point ahead of Oriani.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1913-giro-d-italia] Only the first seven riders could be ranked by the jury, the rest was put ex aequo on the eighth place.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1913-giro-d-italia] Bordin won the sprint, with Oriani in second place; this was enough for Oriani to become the new leader in the general classification.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1913-giro-d-italia] The only rider who could take the overall victory away from Oriani was Azzini.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1913-giro-d-italia] Midway in the stage, Oriani had a flat tire.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1913-giro-d-italia] He changed a wheel with his team mate Agostoni, and had to chase the main group (including Azzini).
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1913-giro-d-italia] Azzini rode hard to stay away from Oriani, but Oriano was able to get back to Azzini's group, and when he saw that Azzini was tired, he immediately rode away.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1913-giro-d-italia] Some riders followed him, but Azzini was not able to follow.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1913-giro-d-italia] Oriani's escape group stayed away until the finish, and Oriani thus won the Giro.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1913-giro-d-italia] There were 35 cyclists who had completed all nine stages.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1913-giro-d-italia] There was a classification for only the *isolati* riders that was called the "Premio Momo," it was calculated in the same manner as the general classification.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1913-giro-d-italia] To be eligible for the team classification, known in Italian as the *Premio dell'Industria*, the team must have three riders complete the course.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1913-giro-d-italia] For each team that had at least the necessary three riders complete the race, the three riders with the lowest point totals from the team would be added together to give each team its score.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1913-giro-d-italia] The team with the lowest total of points was the winner of the classification.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1913-giro-d-italia] Upon winning the race, Carlo Oriani enlisted in the Corps of the Bersaglieri, the Italian infantry, and got commissioned into World War I.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1913-giro-d-italia] Oriani died in a military hospital in Casserta.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1913-giro-d-italia] The 1913 Giro was considered successful; there were few irregularities, and all but two stages had successful escapes.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1914-giro-d-italia] The **1914 Giro d'Italia** was the sixth *Giro*; it was organised and sponsored by the newspaper *La Gazzetta dello Sport*.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1914-giro-d-italia] The race began on 24 May in Milan with a stage that stretched 420 km (261 mi) to Cuneo, finishing back in Milan on 6 June after a 420.3 km (261 mi) stage and a total distance covered of 3,162 km (1,965 mi).
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1914-giro-d-italia] The race was won by the Italian rider Alfonso Calzolari of the Stucchi team.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1914-giro-d-italia] Second and third respectively were the Italian riders Pierino Albini and Luigi Lucotti.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1914-giro-d-italia] It was the last Giro before the Great War and the first one with a final classification based on time rather than points.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1914-giro-d-italia] It is remembered as the hardest Giro of the heroic period of bicycle racing.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1914-giro-d-italia] Besides five stages of over 400 km (and the longest ever average stage length), it included the longest stage ever in the history of the Giro: the Lucca-Rome stage won by Costante Girardengo.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1914-giro-d-italia] This edition of the Giro was run at the lowest average speed (23.374 km/h); marked the highest gap between the first and the second (1 hour, 55 minutes and 26 seconds); saw the longest ever stage by time taken (the Bari-L'Aquila).
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1914-giro-d-italia] Only 8 riders (out of 81 participants) finished the race.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1914-giro-d-italia] The sixth stage (Bari-L'Aquila) is remembered as the hardest stage in the history of the Giro, with many riders forced to retire, including the first of the general classification Giuseppe Azzini, who was found the next day resting in a country house.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1914-giro-d-italia] The Giro organisation declared Calzolari winner after the race, but a legal battle started between the Giro organisation and the Italian Cycling Union, who thought Calzolari should have been removed from the race for taking help from a car, making Albini the winner.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1914-giro-d-italia] After 14 months in court, the final decision was in favor of the Giro organisation, thus making Calzolari the definitive winner.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1914-giro-d-italia] Before the race started, 98 cyclists had entered themselves in the race, of which 35 were professional cyclists in a team, 41 were professional cyclists without a team, and 22 were amateurs (Italian: *aspiranti*).
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1914-giro-d-italia] Favorites for the race were Lucien Petit-Breton from France, and Ganna, Galetti, Girardengo, Giuseppe Santhià and Azzini from Italy.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1914-giro-d-italia] There was no fixed number for cyclists per team; teams could decide for themselves how many riders to enter.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1914-giro-d-italia] Bianchi sent 8 riders, while Stucchi and Globo only sent 4 riders.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1914-giro-d-italia] Race director Cougnet decided to allow amateurs due to the low number of cyclists and teams that had registered in the weeks prior to the start.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1914-giro-d-italia] Many of these riders were unemployed and borrowed bikes in order to participate.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1914-giro-d-italia] Umberto Ripamonti was the youngest to enter the race at age nineteen.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1914-giro-d-italia] At 24 May, when the Giro began, 81 of them started the race; only eight of them made it to the finish in Milan on 7 June.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1914-giro-d-italia] There were eight teams that competed in the race: Alcyon, Atala, Bianchi, Ganna, Gerbi, Globo, Maino, and Stucchi.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1914-giro-d-italia] The field featured three former Giro d'Italia champions in the 1909 winner Luigi Ganna, three-time winner Carlo Galetti, Eberardo Pavesi who was a member of the 1912 Atala winning team, and returning champion Carlo Oriani.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1914-giro-d-italia] Other notable Italian riders that started the race included Costante Girardengo, Angelo Gremo, Alfonso Calzolari, and Giovanni Gerbi.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1914-giro-d-italia] Angelo Gremo won the first stage ahead of Carlo Durando and Alfonso Calzolari who finished over thirteen minutes in arrears.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1914-giro-d-italia] After those three finishers, 34 more crossed the line with the last rider finishing 7 hours after Calzolari.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1914-giro-d-italia] Three riders were disqualified for being pulled by cars, which meant that half of the cyclists were already out of the race after the first stage.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1914-giro-d-italia] Calzolari won the second stage, leaving all other riders so far behind that he took the lead.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1914-giro-d-italia] Calzolari stayed safe in the third stage.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1914-giro-d-italia] In that third stage, Lauro Bordin escaped after 15 km, and rode alone for 350 km, which made it the longest (unsuccessful) breakaway in the history of the Giro.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1914-giro-d-italia] Calzolari seemed to be the strongest rider, and was at that point expected to win.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1914-giro-d-italia] From then on, Calzolari's tires started to puncture more than normal.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1914-giro-d-italia] Sometimes at a checkpoint where riders had to place their signatures, or when they had to carry their bicycles.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1914-giro-d-italia] In this way, Calzolari's competition won back some time in the fourth stage, which was won by Giuseppe Azzini, with a margin of over 36 minutes.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1914-giro-d-italia] The fifth stage was also won by Giuseppe Azzini, this time more than an hour ahead of the next cyclist.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1914-giro-d-italia] This is the biggest stage winning margin in Giro history, a record that is practically impossible to ever be broken.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1914-giro-d-italia] Azzini had won back enough time to lead the general classification, and was announced as new leader.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1914-giro-d-italia] Later that evening, he was given a penalty of one minute for taking a shortcut, which would have put him back in second place.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1914-giro-d-italia] Due to unclarity about when this penalty should take effect, he is often still regarded as leader after the fifth stage.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1914-giro-d-italia] The next stage is regarded as the toughest stage in the Giro ever.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1914-giro-d-italia] It was very long, and the weather was terrible.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1914-giro-d-italia] Giuseppe Azzini did not finish this stage; he had last been seen 30 km from the finish.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1914-giro-d-italia] The organisation started a search for Azzini, who was found the next morning.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1914-giro-d-italia] Because Azzini had not finished the stage, this was the first time in Giro history that the winner of a stage did not finish the next stage.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1914-giro-d-italia] Carlo Oriani also abandoned in that stage, which meant that there was no previous Giro winner anymore in the race.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1914-giro-d-italia] Calzolari stayed in the race, and he led the race again.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1914-giro-d-italia] However, he was accused of having been pulled by a car.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1914-giro-d-italia] Previously riders had been expelled from the race for this infraction, but the jury decided to give Calzolari a time penalty of three hours.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1914-giro-d-italia] Calzolari did not get into problems anymore in the last two stages, and thereby won the 1914 Giro d'Italia.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1914-giro-d-italia] The race compared to the previous year's edition featured fewer stages and a longer total distance.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1914-giro-d-italia] The route covered the whole stretch of the country from northwest to southeast in Bari.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1914-giro-d-italia] The prize for winning the race in 1914 was 3,000 lire.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1914-giro-d-italia] The stages in the 1914 Giro were unusually long; stages 1, 3, 6, 7 and 8 are the longest 5 stages in the history of the Giro d'Italia, all over 420 km.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1914-giro-d-italia] There were eight cyclists who had completed all eight stages.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1914-giro-d-italia] For these cyclists, the times they had needed in each stage was added up for the general classification.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1914-giro-d-italia] The cyclist with the least accumulated time was the winner.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1914-giro-d-italia] Enrico Sala won the prize for best ranked isolati rider in the general classification.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1914-giro-d-italia] Of the two cyclists without a team, Sala rode as a professional Italian: *isolato* and Ripamonti as an amateur Italian: *aspirante*.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1914-giro-d-italia] During the race, Calzolari, Canepari and Durando had been given a penalty of 3 hours, for taking help from a car.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1914-giro-d-italia] After the race, the Italian Cycling Union said that the Giro jury had made a wrong decision, and that the three cyclists should have been removed from the race, declaring Albini the winner.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1914-giro-d-italia] The Giro organisation did not agree, and declared that Calzolari stayed the winner.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1914-giro-d-italia] The two parties went to court, and in February 1915 the Giro organisation won, and again after an appeal in July 1915, making Calzolari the definitive winner.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1914-giro-d-italia] Several weeks after the 1914 Giro ended, World War I started.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1914-giro-d-italia] Italy initially stayed neutral, but Italy entered World War I in early 1915, which made it impossible to organize a Giro in the next years, and the planned 1915 edition was cancelled.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1914-giro-d-italia] The 1914 Giro has since been regarded as the hardest Grand Tour of all time.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1914-giro-d-italia] Due to the race's reputation, British author Tim Moore rode the route in autumn of 2012.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1914-giro-d-italia] Moore elected to ride the course in period attire and on a period bicycle.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1914-giro-d-italia] He then published a book where he detailed his exploits entitled *Gironimo!: Riding the Very Terrible 1914 Tour of Italy*.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1919-giro-d-italia] The **1919 Giro d'Italia** was the seventh edition of the Giro d'Italia, a Grand Tour organized and sponsored by the newspaper *La Gazzetta dello Sport*.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1919-giro-d-italia] The race began on 21 May in Milan with a stage that stretched 302.8 km (188 mi) to Trento, finishing back in Milan on 8 June after a 277 km (172 mi) stage and a total distance covered of 2,984 km (1,854 mi).
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1919-giro-d-italia] The race was won by the Italian rider Costante Girardengo of the Stucchi team.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1919-giro-d-italia] Second and third respectively were Italian Gaetano Belloni and Belgian Marcel Buysse.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1919-giro-d-italia] Of 66 riders starting the race, only 15 completed it.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1919-giro-d-italia] The Giro (the first one after the Great War) had the first two stages arriving in the "unredeemed" cities of Trento and Trieste, and was dominated by Girardengo, who won seven stages.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1919-giro-d-italia] The '"eternal second" Gaetano Belloni won his first stage in the Giro.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1919-giro-d-italia] This edition of the race was also characterised by the first stage victory by a Swiss rider and by the first non-Italian cyclist on the final podium: the Belgian Marcel Buysse.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1919-giro-d-italia] Of the 63 riders that began the Giro d'Italia on 21 May, fifteen of them made it to the finish in Milan on 8 June.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1919-giro-d-italia] There were four teams that competed in the race: Bianchi Pirelli, Legnano-Pirelli, Peugeot-Tedeschi, and Stucchi-Dunlop.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1919-giro-d-italia] The *isolati* riders that participated in the race were primarily war veterans.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1919-giro-d-italia] Organizers promised all *isolati* riders at least 180 lire if they reached Milan.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1919-giro-d-italia] The Milan Army Corps carried participants luggage for the race with a Fiat 18 BL lorry that remained after the war.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1919-giro-d-italia] The peloton was almost completely composed of Italians.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1919-giro-d-italia] The field featured two former Giro d'Italia champions in the three-time winner Carlo Galetti and Eberardo Pavesi who was a member of the 1912 Atala winning team.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1919-giro-d-italia] Other notable Italian riders that started the race included Costante Girardengo, Angelo Gremo, Ezio Corlaita, and Giuseppe Santhià.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1919-giro-d-italia] Girardengo was current Italian men's road race champion and was recovering from the Spanish flu.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1919-giro-d-italia] The first stage ended in Trento, which was at that time part of Austria-Hungary, although it had been occupied by Italian soldiers following World War I, and would annexed by Italy later that year.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1919-giro-d-italia] This was the first time that an international border was crossed during the Giro d'Italia.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1919-giro-d-italia] This first stage ended in a small group sprint, won by Costante Girardengo, who thereby became leader.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1919-giro-d-italia] The second stage went to Trieste, also not yet annexed by Italy.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1919-giro-d-italia] This region had been heavily damaged in the war, and roads were in bad condition.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1919-giro-d-italia] At one point, the Tagliamento needed to be crossed, but the bridge had collapsed.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1919-giro-d-italia] Riders had to cross the water by foot, carrying their bikes.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1919-giro-d-italia] Girardengo won that stage after a solo escape, and remained leader.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1919-giro-d-italia] The third stage ended in a bunch sprint, but now Girardengo was beaten to second place by Oscar Egg.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1919-giro-d-italia] The fourth stage was 411 km, only seven stages have been longer in the Giro.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1919-giro-d-italia] In that stage, Corlaita and Lucotti escaped and stayed away until the finish, taking more than eight minutes on all the other riders.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1919-giro-d-italia] Girardengo stayed on top of the general classification.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1919-giro-d-italia] He was the favourite to win, but the race was not yet seen as decided.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1919-giro-d-italia] In the fifth stage, Girardengo did better.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1919-giro-d-italia] He was part of the first group of four riders that finished more than 17 minutes ahead of the rest.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1919-giro-d-italia] In the sprint he lost against Belloni, but in the general classification he increased his leading margin to 23 minutes.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1919-giro-d-italia] From then on, there were five more stages.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1919-giro-d-italia] While waiting for the second rider to arrive, he was interviewed by Emilio Colombo, who asked Girardengo how he would like to be called.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1919-giro-d-italia] Girardengo told Colombo to do what he thought best, and Colombo decided to call him the Champion of Champions (*ti chiamerò campionissimo*).
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1919-giro-d-italia] This name would be used for Girardengo for the rest of his career.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1919-giro-d-italia] There were fifteen cyclists who had completed all ten stages.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1919-giro-d-italia] Giosuè Lombardi won the prize for best ranked independent rider in the general classification.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/1919-giro-d-italia] There was a points based classification for the race.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/2017-giro-d-italia] The **2017 Giro d'Italia** was the 100th edition of the Giro d'Italia, one of cycling's Grand Tour races.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/2017-giro-d-italia] The race started on 5 May in Alghero on the island of Sardinia, and ended on 28 May in Milan.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/2017-giro-d-italia] The race was won by Tom Dumoulin, who became the first Dutch male winner of the Giro.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/2017-giro-d-italia] All 18 UCI WorldTeams were automatically invited and were obliged to attend the race.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/2017-giro-d-italia] Four wildcard UCI Professional Continental teams were also selected.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/2017-giro-d-italia] Each team is expected to start with nine riders apart from Astana, with eight riders, due to the death of 2011 winner Michele Scarponi, who died while training days before the start of the race.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/2017-giro-d-italia] The main pre-race favorites were Nairo Quintana (Movistar Team) and Vincenzo Nibali (Bahrain–Merida).
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/2017-giro-d-italia] Sprinters at the Giro include Fernando Gaviria, Caleb Ewan, André Greipel, Jasper Stuyven, Sacha Modolo, Giacomo Nizzolo, Sam Bennett and Ryan Gibbons.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/2017-giro-d-italia] Details about the first three stages of the race were unveiled at a press conference on 14 September 2016.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/2017-giro-d-italia] The remainder of the route was unveiled by race director Mauro Vegni on 25 October 2016.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/2017-giro-d-italia] However, organizers RCS Sport leaked the route on their website the day before the official presentation.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/2017-giro-d-italia] There were 21 stages in the race, covering a total distance of 3,609.1 km (2,243 mi), 142 km (88.2 mi) longer than the 2016 Giro.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/2017-giro-d-italia] The longest race stage was stage 12 at 229 km (142 mi), and stage 14 the shortest at 131 km (81 mi).
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/2017-giro-d-italia] The race featured a total of 69.1 km (43 mi) in individual time trials, and five summit finishes: stage 4, to Mount Etna; stage 9, to Blockhaus; stage 14, to Oropa; stage 18, to Ortisei/St.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/2017-giro-d-italia] The Cima Coppi (the race's highest elevation) was the Stelvio Pass, summited during stage 16.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/2017-giro-d-italia] The stages were categorised in four ways by race organisers; time trials, low, medium and high difficulty.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/2017-giro-d-italia] Lukas Pöstlberger won the first stage, André Greipel claimed the second and Fernando Gaviria the third.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/2017-giro-d-italia] From there Bob Jungels would wear the Pink jersey as Gaviria went on to win three more stages and lock up the points classification.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/2017-giro-d-italia] As the race entered the mountains the leader's jersey swapped between Nairo Quintana and Tom Dumoulin going into the penultimate time trial where Quintana was in 1st and Dumoulin in 4th.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/2017-giro-d-italia] Domenico Pozzovivo, Ilnur Zakarin, Vincenzo Nibali and Thibaut Pinot, who had just won the final mountain stage, were all within 90 seconds of Quintana.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/2017-giro-d-italia] During the final time trial Dumoulin finished 2nd to fellow Dutchman Jos van Emden, but beat all of the GC contenders handily claiming the Giro victory thirty seconds ahead of Quintana as Nibali finalized the podium.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/2017-giro-d-italia] This was the first grand tour victory by a Dutch rider in nearly four decades.
[src:2017-giro-d-italia/2017-giro-d-italia] With the team incurring first and second AAFs within a twelve-month period, the UCI aimed to enforce article 7.12.1 of the UCI Anti-Doping Rules, allowing for suspension of the team from 15 to 45 days – casting doubt on their Giro appearance.
